    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://jamailfloors.com/blog/hardwood-flooring-houston-humidity" }
  })}></script>

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-linear-to-b from-brand-sand/60 via-brand-ivory to-white pointer-events-none"></div>
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-16 pb-10 max-w-3xl">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-xs text-brand-ink/60 mb-4">
        <a href="/blog" class="text-brand-brass hover:underline">← Blog</a>
        <span class="opacity-50">·</span>
        <span class="font-semibold text-brand-brass uppercase tracking-wider">Installation</span>
        <span class="opacity-50">·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">Hardwood Flooring in Houston's Humidity: What Actually Works</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>Houston humidity is unlike anywhere else in the country. Summer 90%+ relative humidity, winter 30–40% RH, slab-on-grade construction holding moisture year-round. It's the single biggest cause of hardwood floor failures in Houston homes. Most of them are preventable.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">Quick truth: <strong>solid hardwood fails in Houston. Engineered hardwood works — if installed correctly.</strong> The rest of this article explains why and what "correctly" looks like.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">How wood moves with humidity</h2>
    <p>Wood is hygroscopic — it absorbs and releases moisture from the air. As humidity rises, wood expands. As humidity falls, wood contracts. This isn't a flaw; it's just how wood works.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In Denver (40% RH year-round), wood floors barely move. In Houston (35% in February, 85% in July), they move significantly. Over a 12-month cycle, a properly installed hardwood floor in Houston expands and contracts more than the same floor would in 90% of the country.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Why solid hardwood fails</h2>
    <p>Solid hardwood is one continuous piece of wood from top to bottom — usually 3/4" thick. The entire board moves with humidity changes. In Houston:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Cupping</strong> — boards bow up at the edges from absorbed moisture</li>
      <li><strong>Crowning</strong> — boards bow up in the middle from rapid drying</li>
      <li><strong>Gapping</strong> — visible gaps between boards in winter when boards shrink</li>
      <li><strong>Buckling</strong> — boards lift entirely off the subfloor (worst case)</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Solid hardwood works in Houston if it's installed in a tightly humidity-controlled environment with extensive acclimation and tight installation. It rarely is. Most installers won't even attempt solid hardwood here anymore — it's a callback factory.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Why engineered hardwood works</h2>
    <p>Engineered hardwood is a real-oak wear layer (usually 3–4mm) bonded to a stable plywood or HDF core. The cross-grain construction of the core resists movement — even when the oak surface wants to expand or contract, the engineered base holds it in place.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In Houston humidity swings, engineered hardwood may move 20–30% as much as solid hardwood would. That's well within tolerance for a properly installed floor.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What "installed correctly" means in Houston</h2>
    <p>Four things absolutely matter, and most failures come from skipping one of them:</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">1. Acclimation (48–72 hours minimum)</h3>
    <p>Material delivered to your home, opened to your home's air, given time to equalize before installation. Skip this and the boards will install at one moisture content, then expand/contract dramatically when they reach equilibrium. Cupping in month 3.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">2. Moisture testing the slab</h3>
    <p>Houston slabs routinely test high for moisture (>4 lbs/sqft/24 hr calcium chloride, >75% RH probe). Adhesive can fail when moisture wicks through the slab. We moisture-test every slab. If it tests high, we apply a roller-on moisture-mitigation coating that cures overnight. Skipping this step is the #1 cause of glue-down failures in Houston.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">3. Proper acclimation of subfloor</h3>
    <p>The slab itself should be at stable humidity. Brand-new construction slabs are still drying for 6+ months. Installing hardwood over a green slab will fail. We won't install over slabs less than 60 days old.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">4. Expansion gap at perimeter</h3>
    <p>Hardwood needs room to expand against walls. Every wall transition should have at least 1/4" expansion gap hidden under the baseboard. Floors installed tight against walls cup and buckle as they expand.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What about HVAC?</h2>
    <p>Keeping your home's interior humidity between 35–55% RH year-round is ideal for hardwood. Most Houston homes have AC running 8+ months a year, which keeps summer humidity reasonable. The risk window is the off-season — March/April and October/November — when AC isn't running but humidity is high.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">A whole-home humidifier (winter) or dehumidifier (shoulder season) helps. Not essential, but smart for premium installations.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Bottom line: how to specify a humidity-proof floor in Houston</h2>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Engineered construction (5/8"+ thick, 4mm+ wear layer, quality core)</li>
      <li>European white oak for tightest grain and best stability</li>
      <li>Installer that delivers material 48–72 hours pre-install</li>
      <li>Installer that moisture-tests slab and applies mitigation if needed</li>
      <li>Expansion gaps at every wall (hidden by baseboard)</li>
      <li>Reasonable interior humidity control year-round</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">Specify all six, and your floor will look identical at year 10 to the day it was installed. Skip any of them and you'll see problems before year 2.</p>

  </article>

